<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-242-690  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 242 690.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Learning  May 1989 v8 n7 p38(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Hand scanners: an inexpensive and easy way to capture graphics.andO;(buyers guide)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Hertzberg, Lanny.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Hand-held scanners are an inexpensive and easy way to capturegraphics, but many schools have held off purchasing scanners forthree reasons: the prices have been high, there is a lack ofinformation about them, and their performance was perceived aspoor.andP;  There are two types of scanners: those that scan graphics,and those that are capable of optical character recognition (OCR).andO;Full page OCR scanners range in price from $1,000 to over $20,000,a prohibitive price range for most schools.andP;  Hand-held scannersare a relatively new and comparatively economical answer.andP;  Fivehand scanners in the $150 to $400 price range are compared.andP;  TheComplete Hand Scan 400 was considered the most comfortable to use.andO;The documentation for products by The Complete PC Inc wereconsidered the best.andP;  Logitech's Scan Man has the widest varietyof utility files and Windows support.andP;  All of these scanners wouldbe extremely useful in a school situation.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Complete PC Inc. (products)Logitech Inc. (products)Diamond Flower Electric Instrument Company (USA) Inc. (products)NISCA Inc. (products).andO;Product:   Complete Hand Scan 400 (Scanning device) (evaluation)Complete Hand Scan Half-page (Scanning device) (evaluation)LogiTech ScanMan (Scanning device) (evaluation)DFI Handy Scanner HS-3000 (evaluation)NISCA Niscan (Scanning device) (evaluation).andO;Topic:     ScanningI-O DevicesOptical Character Readers.andO;Feature:   illustrationtablephotograph.andO;Caption:   Hand scanners. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>